I2C (Inter-Integrated Circuit) is a serial communication protocol used to connect multiple sensors and devices to a microcontroller using only two communication lines. It is widely used in IoT systems because it reduces wiring and allows multiple devices to communicate on the same bus.

SDA and SCL Lines

SDA (Serial Data): Transfers data between the microcontroller and I2C devices.
SCL (Serial Clock): Provides the clock signal to synchronize data transfer.

How I2C Addressing Works

Each I2C device has a unique address (usually 7-bit).
The microcontroller (master) sends the address of the device it wants to communicate with.
Only the device with the matching address responds, while the others ignore the communication.
This allows multiple sensors to share the same SDA and SCL lines.

Three Common IoT Sensors Using I2C

BMP280 – Temperature and Pressure Sensor
MPU6050 – Accelerometer and Gyroscope Sensor
BH1750 – Light Intensity Sensor
